{"id":"nucl-th/9307006","submitter":null,"authors":"M. Prakash, P.J. Ellis, E.K. Heide and S. Rudaz","title":"Neutron Stars and Nuclei in the Modified Relativistic Hartree\n  Approximation","comments":"33 pages, Latex, 8 figures (available from authors by fax), Minnesota\n  preprint NUC-MINN-93/7-T","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1016/0375-9474(94)90376-X","report-no":null,"categories":"nucl-th","license":null,"abstract":"  We have examined the properties of neutron-rich matter and finite nuclei in\nthe modified relativistic Hartree approximation for several values of the\nrenormalization scale, $\\mu$, around the standard choice of $\\mu$ equal to the\nnucleon mass $M$. Observed neutron star masses do not effectively constrain the\nvalue of $\\mu$. However for finite nuclei the value $\\mu/M=0.79$, suggested by\nnuclear matter data, provides a good account of the bulk properties with a\nsigma mass of about 600 MeV. This value of $\\mu/M$ renders the effective three\nand four body scalar self-couplings to be zero at 60\\% of equilibrium nuclear\nmatter density, rather than in the vacuum. We have also found that the matter\npart of the exchange diagram has little impact on the bulk properties of\nneutron stars.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 6 Jul 1993 22:26:11 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-10-22"}
